4. DOCKER IMAGES:
====================
.  A Docker image is a read-only template that contains a set of instructions for creating a container that can run on the Docker Platform.

# docker run hello-world

Docker image is made up of a collection of files that bundle together all the essentials, such as installations, 
  application code and dependencies, required to configure a fully operational container environment.
- we can create an image in two way.

manual Method:
--------------
 By running a container from an existing Docker image manually changing that container environment through a 
 series of live steps and saving the resulting state as a new image.
Automated Method: 
------------------
 By constructing a plain-text file known as a Dockerfile, which provides the specifications for creating a Docker Image.

4.1.To login to docker hub or any other registry
-------------------------------------------------

# docker login


4.2. To seach images 
-----------------------
# docker search <image name>
# docker search httpd

4.3 Downloading Docker Images:
------------------------------
To pull images (if you dont specify the version it will pull image with latest tag)
# docker pull <image name>
# docker pull httpd

To pull a specific version of image
# docker pull <image name:version>
# docker pull httpd:2.4

4.2. List Images:
------------------
# docker images or docker image ls
# docker images
# docker images -q    ---only list image ID.

TAG − This is used to logically tag images.
Image ID − This is used to uniquely identify the image.
Created − The number of days since the image was created.
Virtual Size − The size of the image.

4.3. Removing Docker Images:
------------------------
To Delete Images

# docker rmi
# docker rmi ImageID

To remove all dangling images
#docker image prune

To remove all images which doesn't have a container associated with them
# docker image prune -a

4.4. docker inspect Images:
----------------------------
To know details about an image

# docker inspect <image name>
# docker inspect httpd


4.5. Docker Image history:
----------------------------
To look at the history of an image

# docker image history <image name>
# docker image history httpd


4.6. Filter Dangling Images:
-----------------------------
To filter dangling images

# docker images -f dangling=true
